## Setting Up a Custom Color Palette for Mobile-First Responsive Design in Tailwind CSS

### **Tailwind CSS v4 (Latest - 2024/2025)**

In v4, Tailwind moved to a **CSS-first approach** using the `@theme` directive instead of JavaScript config files.

#### 1. Define Custom Colors with `@theme`

In your main CSS file (e.g., `app.css` or `globals.css`):

```css
@import "tailwindcss";

@theme {
  /* Primary brand colors */
  --color-primary-50: #eff6ff;
  --color-primary-100: #dbeafe;
  --color-primary-200: #bfdbfe;
  --color-primary-300: #93c5fd;
  --color-primary-400: #60a3fa;
  --color-primary-500: #3b82f6;
  --color-primary-600: #2563eb;
  --color-primary-700: #1d4ed8;
  --color-primary-800: #1e40af;
  --color-primary-900: #1e3a8a;
  --color-primary-950: #172554;

  /* Secondary/accent colors */
  --color-accent: #f97316;
  --color-success: #22c55e;
  --color-warning: #eab308;
  --color-error: #ef4444;

  /* Semantic colors for theming */
  --color-background: #ffffff;
  --color-foreground: #0f172a;
  --color-muted: #64748b;
}
```

This automatically generates utility classes like `bg-primary-500`, `text-accent`, `border-error`, etc.

#### 2. Dark Mode Support

```css
@theme {
  --color-background: #ffffff;
  --color-foreground: #0f172a;
}

.dark {
  --color-background: #0f172a;
  --color-foreground: #f8fafc;
}
```

---

### **Tailwind CSS v3 (Still Widely Used)**

#### 1. Configure `tailwind.config.js`

```javascript
/** @type {import('tailwindcss').Config} */
module.exports = {
  content: ['./src/**/*.{html,js,jsx,ts,tsx}'],
  darkMode: 'class', // or 'media' for system preference
  theme: {
    extend: {
      colors: {
        // Full color scale
        primary: {
          50: '#eff6ff',
          100: '#dbeafe',
          200: '#bfdbfe',
          300: '#93c5fd',
          400: '#60a3fa',
          500: '#3b82f6',  // Default
          600: '#2563eb',
          700: '#1d4ed8',
          800: '#1e40af',
          900: '#1e3a8a',
          950: '#172554',
        },
        // Simple single colors
        accent: '#f97316',
        success: '#22c55e',
        warning: '#eab308',
        error: '#ef4444',
      },
    },
  },
  plugins: [],
}
```

---

### **Mobile-First Responsive Usage**

Tailwind is **mobile-first by default**. Breakpoint prefixes apply styles at that size **and up**:

| Prefix | Min-width | CSS |
|--------|-----------|-----|
| (none) | 0px | Mobile base styles |
| `sm:` | 640px | Small tablets |
| `md:` | 768px | Tablets |
| `lg:` | 1024px | Laptops |
| `xl:` | 1280px | Desktops |
| `2xl:` | 1536px | Large screens |

#### Example: Responsive Color Usage

```html
<!-- Background changes at different breakpoints -->
<div class="bg-primary-100 sm:bg-primary-200 md:bg-primary-300 lg:bg-primary-400">
  Responsive background
</div>

<!-- Text color with dark mode -->
<p class="text-foreground dark:text-white md:text-primary-700">
  Responsive text
</p>

<!-- Card with responsive padding and colors -->
<div class="
  bg-white dark:bg-gray-900
  p-4 sm:p-6 md:p-8
  text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100
  border border-primary-200 dark:border-primary-800
  rounded-lg md:rounded-xl
">
  Mobile-first card
</div>
```

---

### **Best Practices**

1. **Use semantic color names** (`primary`, `accent`, `error`) instead of visual names (`blue`, `red`)
2. **Create a full shade scale** (50-950) for flexibility
3. **Use CSS variables** for runtime theme switching
4. **Consider OKLCH color model** (v4 default) for perceptually consistent palettes
5. **Use opacity modifiers** like `bg-primary-500/80` for transparency

